    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-10-06T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-10-06T03:00:00-05:00" n="719"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890F.248/10–644: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tuck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-10-06T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 6, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 5:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3007. Re No. 7 from Dhahran, October 4.<note n="13" xml:id="d719fn13">Not
                        printed; it reported the visit of two British officers to Dhahran for the
                        purpose of finding a site for a Royal Air Force landing field
                        (890F.248/10–444).</note> From Eddy. Most authentic confidential source
                    confirms that British told Saudi Government to refuse aerodrome to US Army at
                    Dhahran. Royal Air Force Chief Cairo stated to same source that Air Ministry
                    London would not concur in US Army request for Dhahran aerodrome.</p>
                <p>In view of British survey for Dhahran airfield this appears to be an unfriendly
                    act constituting (1) anti-American coercion of Saudi Government (2) obstruction
                    to Allied war effort. Perhaps it is test of equal opportunities for US and of
                    British cooperation in Saudi Arabia.<note n="14" xml:id="d719fn14">For
                        correspondence relating to the American-British joint supply program in
                        Saudi Arabia, see <ref target="#pg_670">pp. 670</ref> ff.</note> [Eddy.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tuck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
